    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>JUMP ROPE MAGIC</p>
        <p>By Afi Scruggs.</p>
        <p>Illustrated by David Diaz.</p>
        <p>Blue Sky/Scholastic, $16.95.</p>
        <p>(Ages 2 to 5)</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>JUMP ROPE MAGIC</p>
        <p>By Afi Scruggs.</p>
        <p>Illustrated by David Diaz.</p>
        <p>Blue Sky/Scholastic, $16.95.</p>
        <p>(Ages 2 to 5)</p>
        <p>Shameka, the main character of the delightful new book ''Jump Rope Magic,'' is a girl on the move. ''I'm the girl with the motion, / wave my hands like the ocean. / I can jump so high, / till I reach the sky,'' she says as she flies out of her jump rope into the air over a pastel cityscape.</p>
        <p>In her first book using bouncy rhyme sprinkled with jazzy call-and-response (''Hey crew!'' / ''What?'' / ''Are you ready?'' / ''For what?'' / ''To jig!'' / ''Jig what?'' / Jig-a-low!'' / ''Let's go!''), Afi Scruggs tells the story of Shameka, a lively jump-roper, and her crew. She and her merry friends make a little too much joyful noise with their familiar jump-rope rhymes, disturbing Miss Minnie, their worrywart neighbor. Eventually, though, even grouchy Miss Minnie is swept up in the joyful rhythms and ends up getting her own jump-rope groove on. The verse is complemented by the loose-limbed illustrations of David Diaz, whose ''Smoky Night'' won the Caldecott Medal for 1994. Against cotton-candy-colored backdrops, his playful figures resemble apple-cheeked marionettes, his style falling somewhere between realism and whimsy. They add to the energy of this magical, spunky book.</p>
        <p>Linda Villarosa</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
